<div id="review_466015108" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/466015108" />
    <a title="Mary Novaria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2623473-mary-novaria"><img alt="Mary Novaria" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1464908992p2/2623473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/466015108?book_show_action=true">Nov 29, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mary Novaria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mary Novaria" href="/user/show/2623473-mary-novaria">Mary Novaria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer466015108" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2038126105846855910">Jim Beaver’s raw and beautiful memoir, at its core, is a love story. The author generously shares a year in his life—a year that would cause many of us to pull the covers over our heads and not emerge for a long, long time. The story begins with news of his wife Cecily’s shocking Stage IV cancer--just months after the couple’s toddler Maddie is diagnosed with autism. <br/><br/>The saga begins in the form of a nightly email to a growing list of family and friends, apprising them of Cecily’s status. But Bea</span>
  <span id="freeText2038126105846855910" style="display:none">Jim Beaver’s raw and beautiful memoir, at its core, is a love story. The author generously shares a year in his life—a year that would cause many of us to pull the covers over our heads and not emerge for a long, long time. The story begins with news of his wife Cecily’s shocking Stage IV cancer--just months after the couple’s toddler Maddie is diagnosed with autism. <br /><br />The saga begins in the form of a nightly email to a growing list of family and friends, apprising them of Cecily’s status. But Beaver’s missives quickly move from medical updates to bravely honest accounts of his disbelief, anger, terror, guilt, grief and, most of all, love. The story is engaging and authentic as Beaver prays for a cure, loses his soul mate, becomes a single parent to Maddie and, somehow, manages to pepper it all with a warm, self-deprecating humor. <br /><br />Don’t be put off by the subject of death—there is nothing maudlin about this book. <i>Life’s That Way</i> is far more about living, loving, friendship and honor. Beaver graciously takes us on the journey with him and, though we share in his profound loss, we also get to share in the hope that follows. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2038126105846855910" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


