    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_53916146" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/53916146" />
    <a title="Brigita" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1346843-brigita"><img alt="Brigita" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570616247p2/1346843.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/53916146?book_show_action=true">Apr 25, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brigita" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brigita" href="/user/show/1346843-brigita">Brigita</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer53916146" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4300195148684895576">Jim Beaver&apos;s Life&apos;s That Way is the most sincere account about the battle with cancer I&apos;ve ever read. The book is a collection of e-mails Jim sent daily to family and friends about his wife&apos;s struggle with stage IV lung cancer. For most people who have experienced the disease this is indeed a painful read, but it also offers hope and reasons to smile. When Cecily was diagnosed, an unbelievable number of family members and friends offered to help in any way they could, making Cecily, Jim, and the</span>
  <span id="freeText4300195148684895576" style="display:none">Jim Beaver's Life's That Way is the most sincere account about the battle with cancer I've ever read. The book is a collection of e-mails Jim sent daily to family and friends about his wife's struggle with stage IV lung cancer. For most people who have experienced the disease this is indeed a painful read, but it also offers hope and reasons to smile. When Cecily was diagnosed, an unbelievable number of family members and friends offered to help in any way they could, making Cecily, Jim, and their little Maddie feel a little less alone in their fight.<br /><br />Jim is honest in relating his thoughts and emotions. Reading about his anger, resentment at the unfairness of the disease, and profound fear makes it easier for people to accept these feelings when they experience them themselves.<br /><br />This is a touching, heart-breaking book everyone should read. Not only because almost everyone knows someone who had cancer or even had it themselves, but because it can teach us about our own strength and courage when they're needed, and that human kindness and selflessness has no limits.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4300195148684895576" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


